"Harris R.N., Chapman D.S.","Borehole temperatures and a baseline for 20th-century global warming estimates",1997,"Science","275","5306",,"1618","1621",,,10.1126/science.275.5306.1618,"http://www.scopus.com/inward/record.url?eid=2-s2.0-0030620641&partnerID=40&md5=971b0cb7456c7206d97e959f100d6a08","Department of Geology and Geophysics, University of Utah, Salt Lake City, UT 84112, United States","Harris, R.N., Department of Geology and Geophysics, University of Utah, Salt Lake City, UT 84112, United States; Chapman, D.S., Department of Geology and Geophysics, University of Utah, Salt Lake City, UT 84112, United States","Lack of a 19th-century baseline temperature against which 20th-century warming can be referenced constitutes a deficiency in understanding recent climate change. Combination of borehole temperature profiles, which contain a memory of surface temperature changes in previous centuries, with the meteorological archive of surface air temperatures can provide a 19th- century baseline temperature tied to the current observational record. A test case in Utah, where boreholes are interspersed with meteorological stations belonging to the Historical Climatological Network, yields a noise reduction in estimates of 20th-century warming and a baseline temperature that is 0.6°± 0.1°C below the 1951 to 1970 mean temperature for the region.",,"air temperature; article; climate; environmental temperature; greenhouse effect; meteorology; priority journal; surface property; baseline temperature; borehole temperature; climate change; global warming",,,,,,"Hansen, J., Lebedeff, S., (1987) J. Geophys. Res., 92, p. 13345; Jones, P.D., Wigley, T.M.L., Briffa, K.R., (1994) Trends '93: A Compendium of Data on Global Change, pp. 603-608. , T. A. Boden, D. P. Kaiser, R. J. Sepanski, F. W. Stoss, G. M. Logsdon, Eds. Carbon Dioxide Information Analysis Center, Oak Ridge National Laboratory, Oak Ridge, TN; Ellsaesser, H.W., MacCraken, M.C., Walton, J.J., Grotch, S.L., (1986) Rev. 